<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900809-0058</DOCNO><DOCID>900809-0058.</DOCID><HL>   Abreast of the Market:   Industrials End Six-Day Decline,   Rising 24.26 as Mideast Fears Ease   ----   By David Wilson   Staff Reporter of the Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/09/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2</SO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)STOCK INDEXES (NDX)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Setting aside its concerns about the turmoilin the Middle East, the stock market advanced for the firsttime this month as investors went looking for bargains.   But the worries about recession that have intensifiedsince Iraq invaded Kuwait and oil prices soared continued tohold sway over the market. Shares of companies expected todeliver better earnings in any economic climate paced themarket's reversal.</LP><TEXT>   The Dow Jones Industrial Average broke a six-sessionlosing streak by gaining 24.26, or 0.9%, to 2734.90. Theaverage had fallen a total of 7.1% during its string ofsetbacks, with most of the loss following the invasion.   Among broader measures, Standard andamp; Poor's 500-Stock Indexclimbed 3.52 to 338.35, the New York Stock Exchange CompositeIndex gained 1.95 to 185.40 and the Dow Jones Equity MarketIndex gained 3.48 to 313.56. Advancing issued totaled 1,015,compared with about 601 decliners.   Although trading remained active, Big Board volume failedto surpass 200 million shares for the first time since theinvasion. Volume reached 190,400,000 shares, compared with231,580,000 Tuesday.   Analysts said the U.S. decision to send troops to SaudiArabia -- in what President Bush and administration officialsdescribed as purely a defensive role -- eased the market'sfears that the Middle East crisis would worsen.   &quot;Bush gained a lot of respect, and I think he's got a lotof people rooting for him now,&quot; said William M. LeFevre, amarket strategist at Advest Inc., Hartford, Conn. &quot;Investorsare convinced that the problem has been contained.&quot;   Share prices rose throughout the morning and peaked atmidday as investors digested the statements from Bush, alongwith statements from Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein saying hewould seek &quot;full unity&quot; of Iraq and Kuwait.   Meanwhile, the rise in oil prices collapsed after theSaudis said they would increase their oil production tooffset losses resulting from the international boycott of oilfrom Iraq and Kuwait. Crude-oil futures fell sharply in NewYork trading, with September contracts on West TexasIntermediate losing $2.35 a barrel to $25.96.   The Dow Jones Transportation Average rose 26.64 to 991.42,its first gain since July 26. A rebound in UAL, whose stockhad fallen 38% since the average last recorded a gain,accounted for most of the latest move.   The plunge in oil prices took its toll on energy stocks.Exxon fell 1 5/8 to 51 3/4 on trading of two million shares,Texaco dropped 1 7/8 to 62 3/4 on 1.7 million shares andChevron went down 1 3/4 to 76 7/8; those losses depressed theindustrial average by about 10 1/2 points.   In response to the Saudis' promise to boost oilproduction, Dean Witter Reynolds recommended that investorscut their cash levels in half, to 10% from 20%. The firmboosted its recommended stock and bond allocations by fivepercentage points each, to 70% and 20%, respectively.   John D. Connolly, chairman of the firm's investmentcommittee, said the recommended cash position had been raisedfrom zero to 20% immediately after the Iraqi invasion. As aresult of the Saudi decision, &quot;The dire outlooks aboutrecession will have to be rethought,&quot; Mr. Connolly said.   Investors snapped up consumer stocks with a track recordof earnings improvement, along with other growth stocks.   Philip Morris added 3/8 to 45 5/8 on three million shares,Coca-Cola gained 1 5/8 to 44 and Procter andamp; Gamble jumped 23/4 to 80.   Boeing rallied 1 to 53 on two million shares and WasteManagement rose 1 1/2 to 39 1/8 on 1.5 million shares.   SmithKline Beecham equity units rose 3 1/2 to 46 7/8,pacing an across-the-board rally among drug stocks, as 1.3million issues were traded. The British-based companyreported a 6% increase in second-quarter pretax profit from ayear earlier.   Alza climbed 2 1/2 to 43 1/4 on the American StockExchange. The Food and Drug Administration granted marketingapproval to a treatment for chronic pain which uses Alza'sdrug-delivery system to administer a drug produced by a unitof Johnson andamp; Johnson.   Johnson andamp; Johnson rose 1 7/8 to 67 1/8. Among other majorpharmaceutical issues, Merck rose 2 1/8 to 85 1/8,Bristol-Myers Squibb rose 1 3/8 to 61 1/2, Schering-Ploughgained 1 1/4 to 46 1/2, American Home Products went up 2 1/8to 47 7/8 and Eli Lilly added 2 5/8 to 78 3/8 on 1.5 millionshares.   UAL jumped 13 1/2 to 114 1/2, breaking a seven-sessionlosing streak in which the stock plunged a total of 62points. American Banker reported that the union-led groupseeking to acquire United Air Lines' parent company in a$4.38 billion buy-out will ask the UAL board for another 30to 90 days to obtain financing.   Woolworth, which posted a 4.2% increase in second-quarterearnings, advanced 1 1/2 to 28 7/8. Other retailing issues topost sharp gains included Wal-Mart Stores, which went up 15/8 to 30 1/4 on 2.3 million shares; Toys &quot;R&quot; Us, up 1 1/2 to28 1/2; Gap Inc., up 2 3/4 to 53 3/4; and U.S. Shoe, up 1 to15 1/2.   MCA gained 1 1/2 to 47 and CBS climbed 6 3/4 to 176 afterMorgan Stanley cited the two companies as potential takeovertargets for Walt Disney. Analyst Alan Kassan said in a reportto the firm's sales force that he thinks Disney isconsidering a major acquisition, according to Dow JonesProfessional Investor Report. Both Disney and MCA declinedcomment.   Other media and entertainment stocks also rallied,including Disney, which rose 4 5/8 to 108. Eastman Kodak rose1 1/8 to 41 1/8 on 1.5 million shares, ParamountCommunications went up 7/8 to 37 1/4, Time Warner rose 1 to85 3/4 and Mattel added 1 3/8 to 17 7/8.   Ethyl rose 1 5/8 to 30. The company told analysts thatGeneral Motors endorsed its new gasoline additive in a letterdelivered to the Environmental Protection Agency, accordingto the investor report. The EPA is expected to decide by Nov.5 whether to approve the additive, designed to cut autoemissions.   Pep Boys Manny, Moe andamp; Jack added 3/4 to 13 3/4. Standard andamp;Poor's is adding the issue to the Sandamp;P 500 after Monday'sclose to replace General Instrument, the target of a buy-outby Forstmann, Little andamp; Co.   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index rose 0.19to 340.03. Volume totaled 15,020,000 shares.</TEXT></DOC>